    {
        "content": "<p>If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f : A \\to B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> is a bijective-on-objects functor, then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">°</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>:</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">°</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>→</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">°</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[f°, \\mathrm{Set}] : [B°, \\mathrm{Set}] → [A°, \\mathrm{Set}]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mord\">°</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mord\">°</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mord\">°</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> is monadic. Does anyone know where I can find a reference for this fact?</p>",
        "id": 275802834,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1647610556
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't have a reference but this seems to be an easy application of the monadicity theorem: if you have a e.s.o. functor then precomposition is conservative; and in any case, precomposition has both a left adjoint and a right adjoint. But then a conservative functor that preserves coequalisers and has a left adjoint must be faithful, hence monadic.</p>",
        "id": 275813101,
        "sender_full_name": "Zhen Lin Low",
        "timestamp": 1647615248
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, I agree, thank you. But it seems like a useful enough observation that it should be written down somewhere, and I would hope that it has been already: it seems more appropriate to give a reference than to reprove the statement in any paper in which it is needed.</p>",
        "id": 275813416,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1647615394
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm pretty sure I've seen it before somewhere when I was reading about many-sorted algebraic theories.</p>",
        "id": 275813836,
        "sender_full_name": "Zhen Lin Low",
        "timestamp": 1647615585
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In fact, I wrote specifically about the b.o. case <a href=\"http://zll22.user.srcf.net/writing/algebraic-theories/20121121-Main.pdf\">here</a> (1.7.14), hah. Maybe it's in the arities for monads paper.</p>",
        "id": 275814326,
        "sender_full_name": "Zhen Lin Low",
        "timestamp": 1647615734
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's already true when f is just surjective on objects up to retracts (this is how one gets the surjective part in the surjection-inclusion factorization system on essential geometric morphisms between presheaf toposes coming from functors between small categories)<br>\nSo you could quote the relevant example from A4.2 in the Elephant?</p>",
        "id": 275861803,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1647637096
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah yes, it is stated in Example A4.2.7, thank you!</p>",
        "id": 275884792,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1647657957
    }
